  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Funeral Address to Heaven, Composed on Behalf of the Prefect Kim Cheon-jo for His Mother's Memorial
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When parents nurture their children, they expect loyalty and filial piety.
    If one cannot inherit their will, who can claim to possess virtue's essence?
    I consider myself a frail and insignificant creature,
    failing in a son's sacred duty.
    Father departed early into that distant shore,
    and Mother's chambers grew unbearably desolate.
    Yet I, pursuing office and learning, abandoned her side,
    wandering north and south until I reached the capital.
    Small rank brought no achievement, only separation's sting.
    How could I not long to return? Yet shame held me—
    what honor had a poor scholar to offer?

    When the examinations opened, I studied with fervent dedication,
    competing in those testing grounds, and twice—twice!—I passed.
    As a minor official, I came to pay respects;
    her smile, brief and gentle, blessed me.
    Three years I served in the Hanlin Academy, that lowly post.
    Seven more years correcting texts in dusty archives—
    temporary work, vain title, worthless to a son's true purpose.

    In the year of Mushin, I returned home.
    Though worn by age and illness, Mother's eyes still gleamed with clarity.
    When spring came, I prepared to depart.
    I dared not speak of leaving.
    How could I abandon one already old?
    But Mother urged me forward:
    "Why do you linger? Your wife tends the hearth;
    let her hands feed us. Why doubt her care?
    Go forth! Strive for honor, for high position!
    Fulfill your filial duty through success."

    I accepted her teaching and set forth,
    yet my heart harbored unease.
    How many days passed? Scarcely a year.
    Each night I dreamed of her, my spirit soaring toward her chamber,
    until suddenly—the message arrived.
    She was gone.

    Who now do I revere? Who do I lean upon?
    All is finished. All is finished.
    Alas, woe is me!

    Seven sons she bore—a flourishing line.
    The eldest virtuous, the youngest strong,
    each one plowing fields and spinning thread,
    each one dutiful in every season.
    Only I proved unworthy,
    lethargy in my limbs even past my fortieth year,
    studying useless arts, drawing mere ink strokes,
    with barely enough stipend for a single dish.
    Though late success might grant ten thousand measures of grain,
    where would I present them? The ancient sage knew true sorrow:
    "I return bearing rice but have no parent to receive it."
    Time returns not; regret cannot chase yesterday.

    With this single cup of wine I make my offering,
    my sincerity boundless as the ocean.
    Mother, hear these words of grief as if you still drew breath.
    Listen to your son's lament.
  footnotes:
    - 'Mushin year (戊辰): Likely refers to 1388 CE, marking the author''s final visit home'
    - 'Hanlin Academy (翰林): A prestigious but administratively low-ranking position in the Korean court'
    - The reference to bearing rice alludes to the tale of Zengzi from Chinese tradition, who could no longer serve his elderly parents once they had passed, a symbol of ultimate filial regret
